h items were created. Each essay investigates a category of dress-including headgear, pendants and necklaces, body painting, footwear, and facial ornaments-and considers the variations within each of these categories, as well as popular styles and trends through time. The final chapters reveal broader views and comparisons about costume ensembles and their social roles. Shedding new light on the art and archaeology of the ancient Americas, The Adorned Body offers a thorough map of Maya dress that will be of interest to scholars and fashion enthusiasts alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aClothing and dresszCentral America. 0aClothing and dresszMexico. 0aMayasxClothing. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Archaeology.2bisacsh1 aCarter, Nicholas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarter, Nicholas, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCarteret, Alyce De, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Carteret, Alyce, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDobereiner, Jeffrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHouston, Stephen D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHouston, Stephen D., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLukach, Katharine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMatsumoto, Mallory E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRossi, Franco D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRossi, Franco D., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aTremain, Cara Grace, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/32070940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/97814773207164